Here is an implementation of the function in Julia:

```julia
using Markdown

function extract_julia_code(md)
    blocks = map(x -> x.content, filter(x -> x.language == "julia", collect(Markdown.parse(md))));
    code = join(blocks, "\n");
    return code;
end
```
This function uses the `Markdown.jl` package to parse and extract the code blocks from a markdown document with Julia language fences. The function filters out all code blocks in other languages and only retains those for Julia (i.e., where the language is defined as "julia"). It then joins these code blocks together into one string separated by newline characters, and returns this string.

Please note that this solution assumes the input `md` is a valid markdown document in string format. Also, you have to install Markdown package via Pkg.add("Markdown") if not already installed. 

Note: The code blocks can also contain comments starting with `#`, which are removed by joining the blocks together. If you want to keep them, additional processing would be required.
